[
    {
        "content": "<p>It seems like in lean we can only deconstruct hypothesis in form of P \\or Q, P \\and Q. If I want to deal with h:P \\or Q -&gt; R the only thing I can do is apply it to hR:R or the goal R. I'm not that sure if my understanding is correct or not, and this fact seems tedious for me, is there any easier way to deal with that?</p>",
        "id": 508847407,
        "sender_full_name": "Chengyan Hu",
        "timestamp": 1743196920
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>How do you expect this to be destructed?</p>",
        "id": 508847634,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1743197035
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That is, given a <code>h : P ∨ Q → R</code>, what do you want to turn this into to make it easier to use?</p>",
        "id": 508847801,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1743197098
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I mean, I would like to use P-&gt;R and Q-&gt;R</p>",
        "id": 508848644,
        "sender_full_name": "Chengyan Hu",
        "timestamp": 1743197537
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You can <code>rw</code> with <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=or_imp#doc\">docs#or_imp</a></p>",
        "id": 508848833,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1743197644
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And here's a way you can find <code>or_imp</code>:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">q</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">r</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Prop</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∨</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">q</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">r</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">↔</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">((</span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">r</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∧</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">q</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">r</span><span class=\"o\">))</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">exact?</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">-- Try this: exact or_imp</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 508848924,
        "sender_full_name": "Kyle Miller",
        "timestamp": 1743197688
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I see! Thx a lot</p>",
